Introduction

We will create a dataset of 200000 instances seperated into 5 classes. Each instance will have 97 features with roughly a quarter of them being redundant. Also, 40% of the instances will have a random class assigned, that is, there is an error of 40%. Throughout this notebook we will analyse the data and build the most appropriate model to classify this data.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

import tensorflow as tf

tf.config.experimental.set_memory_growth(physical_devices[0], True)

Creating dataset

Like we mentioned previously, we will create a dataset with our assigned variabled. To do this, we will use sklearn's make_classification function. Once created, we will save the data to a csv file so we don't have to create new data everytime. Also, if we did create new data everytime, we couldn't compare the models properly as there would be models trained and tested with different data.

In [ ]:
# User values
seed = 76
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)


features = 97
classes = 5
n = 200000
errors = 0.4
redundant = int(features/4)


# Classification dataset
X, y = make_classification(n_samples=n, n_classes=classes, n_features=features, \
                           random_state = 1,n_informative =20, flip_y=errors, \
                           n_redundant=redundant)

# reshape y to 2D array, it needs to be to append
y = np.reshape(y, (-1, 1))

#add y to x
Xy = np.concatenate((X,y),axis=1)

# Commented to avoid rewriting file
np.savetxt("myCAData.csv", Xy, delimiter=",")

print(Xy[:5])

As we can observe, most of the data if not all, follow a normal distribution with very little skew or outliers. And despite 40% of the instances being assigned a random class, there seems to be an almost equal distribution among the classes. However, we will calculate the number of instances per class in the next cell to confirm this.

From the information available above, we can see that there is very little correlation between any of the features and the class variable. This could result in the accuracy of the model being fairly low as it seems there are no attributes that could have an effect on the class attribute.

Data preprocessing

From the data exploration, we can observe that the distribution of the features is fairly normal with few outliers. Also, as it is a randomised dataset, the features have no real meaning. Therefore, we cannot identify any wrong or impossible values.

However, there is one preprocessing technique we will apply to improve the performance and make the training of the models more efficient. We will normalise the data.

In [ ]:
normData=(data-data.mean())/data.std()
dataset = normData.values

X = dataset[:,0:97]

Model Exploration

Model 1

With model 1, we start with a basic neural network with 2 layers, an input layer and an output layer. The activation function for the input layer is ReLU and for the output layer it is softmax. The output layer will have the same activation function throughout the rest of the notebook. The input layer activation function may change. We will train this model for 10 epochs at the default batch size of 32 using Adam as its optimizer.

In [ ]:
# enocde values to categorical from Int.
encoded_y = to_categorical(y)


# define and fit the final model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(50, input_dim=97, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['acc'])
history = model.fit(X, encoded_y, validation_split=0.33,epochs=10)


# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['acc'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_acc'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Model 2

In an attempt to increase the performance, we will make the network larger by increasing the layers and the number of neurons per layer.

In [ ]:
# enocde values to categorical from Int.
encoded_y = to_categorical(y)


# define and fit the final model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(50, input_dim=97, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(125, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu'))

I believe this is the best performance we will achieve by only modifying the topology and activation function. In the next section we will try this model with 8 different batch sizes.

Batch Sizes

In this section, we will modify the batch size and epochs accordingly to analyse the difference in performance. By changing the batch size, the number of times the weights are updated per epoch varies. Therefore, in data sets with a lot of noise, it could be better to have a larger batch size to ensure that the network learns in the most stable manner possible. In the case of this dataset, there isn't much noise so there shouldn't be much difference between the batch sizes.

Model 7.1

We will try with a batch size of 2000. Of course, by increasing the batch size, we also need to increase the number of epochs to ensure that there is a similar amount of training.

We can see that the accuracy is slightly better when using higher batch sizes and epochs, such as 2000 and 50 respectively.

Grid Search

For the grid search, we will use batch sizes from 1700 to 2200 in intervals of 100. A part from seemingly offering better accuracy in the previous section, the use of bigger batch sizes results in less time to train the model. Using smaller batch sizes in the grid searches would often lead to being timed out by Colab.

Additionally, we will be using the optimizers Adam, Stochastic Gradient Descent and Adamax. The two initializers we have chosen are uniform and random normal.

Each model will be trained for 50 epochs.

Model 7.1

In [ ]:
# enocde values to categorical from Int.
encoded_y = to_categorical(y)


# Function to create model, required for KerasClassifier
def create_model(optimizer='rmsprop', init='glorot_uniform'):
    # create model
    # define and fit the final model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(250, input_dim=97, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=init))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=init))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=init))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation='relu', kernel_initializer=init))
    model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax', kernel_initializer=init))
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['acc'])
    return model

# create model
model = KerasClassifier(build_fn=create_model, verbose=0)

# grid search epochs, batch size and optimizer
optimizers = ['adam', 'sgd', 'adamax']
inits = ['uniform', 'random_normal']
batches = [1700, 1800, 1900, 2000, 2100, 2200]
epochs = [50]
# batches = [32, 128, 256, 512, 1024, 2048]

param_grid = dict(optimizer=optimizers, epochs=epochs, batch_size=batches, init=inits)
grid = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid)
grid_result = grid.fit(X, encoded_y, verbose=1)

# summarize results
print("Best: %f using %s" % (grid_result.best_score_, grid_result.best_params_))
means = grid_result.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = grid_result.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = grid_result.cv_results_['params']

for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    print("%f (%f) with: %r" % (mean, stdev, param))

From the output produced, we can observe that the best model was trained using a batch size of 1900, random normal as the kernel initializer and adam as the optimizer.

However, there is no real difference between the different batch sizes and kernel initializers. The most noticeable difference is the accuracy of Stochastic Gradient Descent compared to Adam and Adamax. This is likely because SGD takes longer to converge the weights of the network than the other two optimizers. Perhaps, if we trained the model for longer with SGD, it would achieve a similar accuracy.

Final Model

In [ ]:
# enocde values to categorical from Int.
encoded_y = to_categorical(y)


# define and fit the final model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(250, input_dim=97, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(10, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))


model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['acc'])
history = model.fit(X, encoded_y, epochs=50, batch_size=1900)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['acc'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# define and fit the final model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(250, input_dim=97, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(50, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(10, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))
model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax', kernel_initializer='random_normal'))


model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['acc'])
model.load_weights('/content/drive/MyDrive/UNI/AIIDL/finalModel.hdf5')

Evaluating Final Model

Creating Unseen Data

We create a random dataset of 2000 instances. We have set a random seed to observe the performance of the model with different unseen datasets.

In [ ]:
import random
# User values
seed = random.randint(0, 7919)
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)


features = 97
classes = 5
n = 2000
errors = 0.4
redundant = int(features/4)


# Classification dataset
X, y = make_classification(n_samples=n, n_classes=classes, n_features=features, \
                           random_state = seed,n_informative =20, flip_y=errors, \
                           n_redundant=redundant)

# reshape y to 2D array, it needs to be to append
y = np.reshape(y, (-1, 1))

#add y to x
Xy = pd.DataFrame(np.concatenate((X,y),axis=1))


data = sk.utils.shuffle(Xy, random_state=seed)

dataset = data.values

X = dataset[:,0:97]
y = dataset[:,97:]
# enocde values to categorical from Int.
encoded_y = to_categorical(y)

Evaluating

In [ ]:
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)
model.evaluate(X, encoded_y)

63/63 [==============================] - 0s 3ms/step - loss: 1.7481 - acc: 0.2020
Out[ ]:
[1.748063564300537, 0.20200000703334808]

From executing the previous 2 blocks of code, we have observed that the accuracy fluctuates between 16% and 24%. This is a big drop in accruacy from the one obtained during the testing of the model.

This could have occured for a various reasons. The model could be overfitted. However, I'm not sure this is the case because the training and testing accuracies are pretty similar. That is, there is very little difference between the two accuracies.

The other reason is that both the training and unseen datasets are randomly generated. Therefore, it is likely that they aren't similar and it is difficult for a neural network to extract the features to correctly classify instances from both datasets.

Summary and Conclusion

We created a random dataset composed of 200000 instances divided into 5 classes and built a neural network to classify instances from said dataset.

We experimented with models of different depths and widths, adjusted the batch sizes and epochs, trialed different optimizers and kernel intializers to achieve the model with the most accuracy. Also, we applied regularisation techinques like dropout layers to reduce overfitting.

We used grid search to determine which configurations performed best.

Finally, we evaluated the model on unseen data and witnessed a big drop in accuracy. We concluded, that it was likely that the datasets used for training and evaluating, were not similar, making it difficult for a neural network to correctly classify instances from both datasets.
